		<h3>What causes acne?</h3>

		<p>
			As you proceed to puberty, your hormones are commanding your oil glands (sebaceous) to produce too much oil (sebum) but your body
			is not able to handle this efficiently. Hair follicle simply swells up with sebum and tears off. This sparks inflammation in the
			surrounding skin.
		</p>

		<p>
			Acne occurs when excess sebum combines with dead skin cells shed from the epidermis ( top skin). This combination of oil and dead skin
			cells leads to a chemical reaction which produces skin bacteria that turns black in colour – hence the name 'blackhead'. These bacteria
			produce irritating substances that can cause inflammation and other variants of acne .
		</p>

		<p>
			Since hormones fluctuate in the years leading up to menopause, many women in their 40s and 50s get acne.
		</p>

		<p>
			Hereditary too is responsible for acne promotion.
		</p>
